segments.text: So we were talking about there was some diversity and some reasonable respect for that diversity.
In my class, in my freshman group, we had a couple of Jewish guys.
We had three.
at least three Hispanics.
And I may be the wrong one to comment on this, but they probably suffered more discrimination than I knew.
But from my standpoint, those people were all accepted on the basis of their abilities and not on the basis of what they were or what they weren't.
And in my class,
By the time we were seniors, the Corps Commander was Hispanic and still a very good friend of mine.
Was Hector?
Oh, I know Hector well.
And Hector was Corps Commander not because they thought it was time for a Hispanic Corps Commander, but because he was the best.
And he'd earned it.
And nobody would disagree.
So...
I think that's one of the things I always have treasured about the way A&M was at that time was that uniform at the core was a great leveling factor.
And it didn't matter what somebody, what they dressed like when they came or how much money they had or anything at all like that.
It was a matter of what you could accomplish and what was inside you.
Sort of the American ideal.
What were some of the prestigious student activity organizations when you were an undergraduate?
Ah, boy.
Bands, singing cadets, et cetera.
Well, the band was large.
Obviously, everybody had great pride.
Everybody kidded the band, band queers, all that sort of thing, but everybody had great pride in the band and how good it was.
Ross Volunteers was an outstanding organization at the Corps.
Singing Cadets, even now, I think the Singing Cadets
probably aren't appreciated as much by the students as they probably should be because it takes so much time and so much talent to be in that.
There are a lot of other student activities, the student government things, MSC, a lot of those different types of organizations, and that established, in my mind,

what is the importance of education is more than just a classroom because there were so many things down there where students could be involved and learn skills that were probably of greater value in the real world in the business marketplace than what they might learn in the classroom so I've been a very strong advocate of those types of things which if you could have been
had your choice of any of those student leadership roles, which ones do you think had the highest prestige to be the number one person of what, what, what?
Well, I don't know that I've ever tried to rank those.

Being the president of the student body, the president of the student senate at that time, probably was more time consuming and immediately probably had more prestige with the students in some circles.
In many, it probably didn't.
Most of the people who were active in that were regarded as politicians.
And if ever there's been a place where there's probably disdain for student politicians, it's A&M.
The Yale leaders were involved in a lot of things, and that was a prestigious thing.
Being the corps commander was very, very prestigious, I think.
I don't know if there's any one of those that I would think would have been .
Were there any of those organizations, other than the corps commander and, say, the bands, were there any that you all thought always should go to a corps member?
MSC Council, class president, student body president?
I think we probably would have been more inclined to think student body president.
But see, even then,
There was a fellow who was a good friend of mine, civilian student, who was very involved in the MSC and may have been very involved in the student senate who was a civilian student.
There were and have previously been civilian student yell leaders.
I don't think that, I think the culture at that time, my sense is that the culture was not
was not that we need to make sure we have someone in the corps as the head of this, but because it was just sort of assumed that that would be.
I don't think there was a sense of preservation.
It was assumed that the head would always be somebody in the corps.
It was more like, can we let a civilian student be involved?
Well, sure.
It's a little different orientation, if you get my drift.
Okay, one of the interesting little items that I have learned to ask about, can you share anything that you've ever heard about any secret fraternities?
No.
You don't know of any?
You know, I don't.
I had that discussion kind of...
three or four years ago.
I was told that there were some secret fraternities in the Corps that had been uncovered now that they supposedly went back to when I was in school.
I didn't know about it.
I never heard about it as a faculty member for 21 years.
Some of these people I've talked to, 30s and 40s, say yes.
They believe there was the TTs.
And another one, the stickers.
As in swastika.
Well, I'll tell you if you want to stop that.
Let's see.
Project houses.
You didn't have any interaction with anybody that lived over in the project houses?
Well, except to the extent that that was usually married students.
And, of course, you'd have some in your classes.
But, no, I don't remember if I ever even went in one of them.
Let's see.
Let's talk about football weekend.
Describe a typical home game football weekend in College Station.
What happened on Friday and Saturday?
OK. Friday night, you have midnight y'all practice.
Friday afternoons.
you either knew that maybe your parents or friends or maybe if you were lucky enough to have a date, you'd be getting ready for that somehow.
Usually your outfit would have some sort of activity like they'd want to clean up everything or clean up your room, whatever it would be.
Saturdays, if the game was in the afternoon, you'd have the
Describe the yoke practice.
Where was it?
Oh, midnight yoke practice.
Yeah.
Where was it?
What happened?
Make believe I've never been to one.
Well, OK. Let me see if I can remember now.
Midnight yoke practice would start in the core area.
The band would lead it.
Everybody would follow behind the band.
It was sort of like an organized riot.

Of course, not too surprising, a lot of the people had been drinking or whatever, although I don't, I may be wrong, but I don't remember ever seeing people carrying liquor bottles with them at the time because it was, that was a pretty well enforced rule.
But there might have been people who'd been out drinking before that.
And then it would wind around campus,
That's incorrect.
Leave the core area and march down past where the coldness building is now and go into the stadium.
And the midnight yoke practice was held in the stadium.
And my recollection is that it was... Yeah, that's...
Okay.
Whitley.
We were talking about yell practice.
Now what were, you got into the stadium, and then what events occur in the stadium as a part of yell practice?
Well, the idea was built around the regular yell practice.
You had the same formats.
And now I think they use microphones.
I don't remember.

in those days whether they used microphones they may have but i don't remember it wasn't necessary because everything was done by signals and all that but the uh it was extended it was longer than a regular yell practice the
The yell leaders would tell stories, jokes, fables, usually about making fun of the other team that we were playing, or a lot of times about girls.
That was always a popular source of jokes at that time, because there weren't many girls around.
There'd be the band would play.
There may be more to it.
I don't care.
And it would end at about what time?
I think probably about 1 o'clock, something like that.
OK, now let's go to Saturday.
What happened on Saturdays or home games?
Well, let's see.
I don't ever remember.
With certain exceptions, I don't ever remember having a Saturday formation or doing anything with the Corps.
But you'd have to have your room ready for inspection.
If you'd have people coming up, parents or friends or whatever,

If the game was, if it was an afternoon game, we had a lot of night games in those days, if it was an afternoon game, you'd have to be ready by about 11 o'clock, I would think, for a two o'clock game, because they'd have the Corps march into the stadium.
And of course, that was always graded, so you'd have an inspection, they'd have you think that the future of the free world depended upon that, and then you'd march to the stadium,
march around the track, then you'd go off, be dismissed following that, and you'd go sit in the stadium.
I think now they go back to the dorms and change clothes or something like that.
We didn't do that.
We'd go straight to the stadium.
All right, now if you had a date for the game, you parted company with her where?
Usually at the dorm.
And you'd give her your tickets.
And then you'd meet her after the march in up there.
That was one reason it was a little bit more fun, if I remember, to have dates who knew each other.
So several of you could sit together and the dates would know each other.
That made it a little bit more fun.
Describe a court trip.
A court trip.
In those days, there was either one trip a year to Fort Worth or Dallas and one to Houston or Austin.
And so there was really two here, and everybody would go find a place to stay frequently.
You'd have 17 guys at your house if you were from this area.
A lot of play, there'd be core parties if you wanted to go to those.
A lot of guys would use that as an excuse to just go get drunk.
But then on Saturday morning,
Right early, you had to be in either, wherever you were in that downtown area and be ready to march.
And then you'd march in a parade in the downtown of whatever one of those four cities.
Here in Fort Worth, where did y'all gather and where did you march?
In Fort Worth, we would gather actually about three blocks from where we're sitting.
Downtown area, right down here off Main Street.

They changed the parade route several times, but basically you'd march through the downtown area to one end from the north end of downtown to the south and then back up, and it was a pretty good hike.
Fort Worth was a better place to do a parade than a lot of other places.
In Austin, you'd march right down Congress Avenue.
In Houston, I don't remember where we were.
I presume Main Street.
I think so, but I don't remember enough about it.
In Dallas, was it Commerce?
I think probably down Commerce Street.
How did the onlookers on the sidewalks react to a bunch of Aggies marching by?
When you asked that question, my mind immediately thought, did we ever encounter any hostility?
I don't remember anything.
I think it was always parents, friends,
Former students, people who bring their kids.
I used to, gosh, for years after I got out of school, every time A&M would be, the Corps would be here, I'd take my kids down to see them march.
It's just always great.
Always a lot of fun.
What were some of your favorite football game memories?
Do you remember any games that were really special?
Sure.
I remember the...
for various things, for various reasons.
I remember, of course, we beat Texas in 1967.
That meant that we won the conference and went to the Cotton Hole.
That was a great football game.
I remember when I was a freshman or sophomore, I think it was freshman, we played Florida State in College Station.
I don't even remember if we won the game or not, but I remember it rained the whole game.
And we stood in that thing, and it was the wettest game.
I've gone to a few games since then that were pretty wet, but I'll never, that Colorado State game was the top, just everything was wet.
I remember we played SMU one time in the first part of the 1967 season and lost to them right at the end of the game, three or four seconds left.
We thought we were gonna have a good team, and we ended up losing that game too.

I remember coming up here to TCU one year, the year that we won the conference, and a guy intercepted a pass in the end zone by Billy Hobbs for an intercepted pass and ran it back like 102 yards or something for a touchdown.
Yeah, they were a lot of good games.
Final review for you.
Do you have any memories of that being a special?
Yeah, I guess so.
Of course, it's always special when you're a freshman, because that's interesting.
Compare those two, freshman and senior.
Yeah, I was just about to say, I've never thought about that until you asked.
But the same event can mean so many different things to so many different people.
After your freshman year, it's great because it means that you finally survived.
And that doesn't just mean physical survival.
It means you prove something to yourself that you've at least made it so many times when you might question whether you would.
And then your senior year, well, it really means that this is over.
And this is a, you really got to do something now.
And, you know, the factor about this is the last time I'll see most of these guys.
And at that time there was a war going on.
And so you weren't sure exactly what that was, what was going to happen with that.
Did any, did members of your family, any special people there?
Oh yeah, my parents would have been there.
I don't remember if they were there at the final review for my freshman year.
I don't think they were, but I know my senior year they would have been.
That was the same day I graduated and got commissioned.
I graduated in four years.
They were there for that.
That's just one of those things that you remember.
What made commencement special?
Just the fact that I was graduating.
Do you remember who the speaker was?
No, I don't.
I don't.
I've tried to think about that.
And I bet if I went back and looked at my yearbook or really made some effort, I could find it.
And it's probably somebody that I would remember.
I do remember, and I tried to remember this the year I was president of the association.
I remember walking across the stage, and I'm glad to see A&M still does these.

I remember walking across the stage, and President Rudder shook my hand, and then I'm walking towards the end, and I can still remember that Mr. Peterson, Pete Peterson was fourth, and I knew him a little bit.
And he was, I think, probably chairman of the Board of Regents at that time.
And Mr. Peterson came up and shook my hand.
And that meant a lot to me when you see somebody you know doing that.
So I tried to remember when I was president of the association, if I'd see anybody that I knew or knew somebody in their family, I'd speak to them.
But yeah, that was a, in fact, you know, I think kids now graduating, there's a little bit of a sense that they're in the,
They hate to leave because College Station was kind of a cocoon.
In those days, I wanted to get out.
I wanted to go on.
I don't know, I liked it, but I was ready for it to be over.
What kind of a world, you said there was a war going on, what kind of a world did you think you were about to enter?
What was ahead of you as far as you could tell at that point?
I didn't know.
I've always maintained
Until about April, well, until about 60 days or so before I graduated, I wasn't sure what I was going to be doing.
And frankly, what happened was I knew I was going to be commissioned.
And in those days, it was so different than it is now.
I had a friend who suggested, in fact, this is a true story.
It's probably more than you want to know.
There were three or four of us that were talking about going to law school.
And this friend of mine was really the one who was pushing it.
And I figured, well, I'm going to end up in Vietnam.
And he said one time, well, let's go to Austin and see what it takes to get into law school.
Now, this is dumb.
And here we were, seniors about to graduate, and didn't know what it took to get in.
But I figured, I'm going to go to the Army.
Well, three of us went over there.
One of them was Bill Mayholms, the black guy.
So I mean, this almost sounds like a joke.
There were two white guys and a black guy from A&M going to law school.
And we literally went over there to the dean of admissions office and said, we'd like to find out what it takes to get in law school.
And I thought it was going to be some long process.
He said, well, it's simple.
Tell me your grades.
Tell me your LSAT score.
Well, I've taken that because I knew you had to take it and I had that.
He said, that's simple.
That's all.
All you got to tell me.
And so the three of us went around the room and told him.
And it literally was the case where I had the best grades and the best essay possible.
And he told me, he says, you're in.
You apply, you're admitted.
Wow, I'm lying.
And the guy who'd really been the one pushing us was borderline.
He said, I don't know.
You're close.
And Bill, the black guy, had lower grades, lower law school tests.
And he said, well, by your grades, you shouldn't get in.
But I'd like to talk with you some more.
So our friend who commissioned us to go over there on the way back said, well, I can see what's going to happen.
Creel's in, Mayholmes is in, and he says, Bill's gonna end up going to the University of Houston.
That's exactly what happened.
And all of us went on to law school, and all of us have done fairly well.
On that drive back, the one thing that it made me really think seriously about going to law school and pursue it some was that I'd also gone at my friend's behest.
The University of Texas had sent some people over to A&M to talk with students who were interested in studying law school to talk about it.
And I still remember that the guy they sent over
very young professor at the University of Texas named Stanley Johansen.
And Stanley is one of my favorite law school professors and just one of the most remarkable people.
And I remember thinking, this guy is sensational.
And he made it sound interesting.
And then probably a couple of months later, we go over there, and the guy says, you're in if you want to go.
And so I remember thinking on the way back, hey,
I'm going to apply.
I'm going to go over there because I can go there.
And frankly, my thought was maybe by the time I'm through there, this war will be over with and I won't have to go to Vietnam.
So that's what happened.
And so I was eager to go to law school.
And I've often told people, I'm surprised no one's done the study of this.
I don't think that anybody could study the late 60s without realizing
The total cultural divide that existed at that time between Austin and College Station, it was the total difference in cultures between those two places.
In June of 1969, I was in College Station.
In September of 1969, I was resigning in Austin and was likely living in a foreign country.
Did you and your classmates, fellow students, hear any reports of what had happened to Aggies in Vietnam?
Sure, sure.
There was a guy who was a junior in my outfit when I was a freshman.
By the time I was a senior, he'd been killed.
And so we do some things about that.
We hear reports about that.
Did you go to any on-campus musters?
Sure.
Where were they held?
I don't remember any of them being inside G. Raleigh as they are now, but I can remember going to them right in front of the Systems Administration building.
And I think that may be where all of them were.
But I can remember that, so I don't remember going to any of it any other way.
Did those events make any emotional impression on you?
To some extent, yeah.
I don't think that made as much emotional impression on me as Silver Taps did.
I was going to ask you to describe Silver Taps.
Silver Taps occurred in front, actually now to the west of the academic building, right in front of the Saul Ross statue.
That made an emotional impression on me because it was...
It occurred at night.
There was no lights around campus.
And the only sound you could hear was the Ross Volunteers, the firing squad, the Ross Volunteers marching.
And you could hear them for blocks away.
And they'd come and they'd fire taps.
Or they'd come and they'd fire volley.
And then there were a butler that played taps, probably two or three butlers that played taps.
And where were the vehicles?
You know, I'm not sure.
I think they were up, I think they were probably up on the steps of the academic building, but I never identified exactly where.
But that's the place I think they must have been.
As you all left Silver Taps, what was your follow-up attitude and behavior pattern immediately after?
Silence.
nobody spoke a word, and technically you were supposed to have lights out all over the campus.
If you went back and you had to study, you were advised to put a blanket or something up over your window so there wouldn't be, it was like a blackout.
But that made more of an impression on me probably at that age than mustering it.
Right, now let's go to the other extreme.
Where, say on a Saturday night,
If a group of Aggies wanted to go have a good time, cut up, where did people go to kick over the traces?
Well, let's see.
If you were in College Station, there were places that you could go to.
There was some dancing places, I think.
I don't remember if I ever went to one or two of those.
There were some pizza places around that you could go and drink beer and eat pizza.
Not nearly as many places there were.
Was Appalachian still going?
No.
Hard liquor?
No.
Whiskey Bridge?
Whiskey Bridge.
You could go out and buy liquor if you wanted to out west of the county line, out by the river.
Boy, I don't remember.
You can drive into Bryan, go to the movie, or there were some places around.
If you had a special person, either girlfriend or family, where would you have taken them?
We're talking about a positive now, a special.
Sure, sure.
Well, if you wanted to go someplace to eat,
There was a place, I can't remember the name of it.
It was out on that road toward Whiskey Bridge.
It was a steak place.
They had big old steaks.
I can't remember the name of that.
And there were a few other places.
You were out of luck if you didn't like chicken fried steak.
That was about mainly what they had.
There were a couple of little Mexican food places around.
There weren't too many really, not hardly any really nice places I can think of.
Let's see.
Was Pinky still there?
Pinky Downs?
Pinky was there.
Maybe Pinky may have died while I was in school, but I can still remember Pinky walking around.
I'd go just about every morning, I'd go to the MSC.
They had a reading room down there.
I could find the local Fort Worth paper or something.
I'd read that, and I can still remember Pinky hanging out around there, and he'd talk to you.
Did you ever meet old Army Lou?
Oh, sure, sure.
What made him special?
I think that Lupo was special to, I think that for most people who were just buying books, there was the old saying about you're not a true Aggie until you've been screwed by a Lou.
That's what some people used to say.
It was just a place to buy books and he'd always have a line of gab he'd want to talk to you.
give you a dollar for friendship or something like that.
But I've heard too many stories about Aggies who were kind of down on their luck.
And I think that's where he really ingratiated himself was there were a lot of Aggies who needed some money or this or that.
And he really helped a lot of those guys.
And so I think that's where his real legend grew was for helping people.
All right.
We're talking about indulgences now.
Aggies smoked.
What were they smoking?
Winston's, Marlboro's, I guess.
Did you ever hear any, when you were a student, did you ever hear any hint of anybody smoking anything other than tobacco?
God, no.
No.
I don't think any of us knew there was anything else to smoke.
And if they were drinking, they were drinking what?
Well, beer.
liquor, whiskey, just whatever your pleasure was, whatever your personal preference was.
And did anybody chew or dip?
There was some of that, yeah.
The guys who were, you know, mainly the guys who'd grown up in West Texas on ranches or whatever, yeah, there were some guys who did that.
All right, I have never heard any reports of houses of ill repute, prostitution.
In Bryan College Station?
Yeah.
No, there was always a place in LaGrange.
I never went there, but there were guys I knew who did go there.
The chicken ranch was there?
Yeah, yeah.
